Forests are a dominant feature of Canada’s landscape and are central to its economy. Forests enrich the lives of all Canadians, offer a place of sanctuary and recreation and are fundamental to the cultural and spiritual values of Indigenous peoples. Forests provide habitat for wildlife, moderate climate and filter air and water. On International Day of Forests, March , take a moment to Celebrate Canada’s forests.

Happy International Day of Forests! The health and well-being of our nation’s forests matters. Canada is proud of its world-recognized forest management practices. The Government of Canada is committed to the sustainable management of its forests so as to maintain their environmental, social and economic values and benefits over time.

Good evening, Instagram! My name is Vicki Tschirhart, and I’m a geophysicist with the Geological Survey of Canada.Tomorrow, I’m taking over the NRCan Instagram account to give you a glimpse into a day in the life of a geoscientist in the field. Stay tuned!

Hi everyone, and welcome to my summer home! It’s geophysicist Vicki Tschirhart here! My field site is located in the Patterson Lake corridor, southwestern Athabasca Basin, a region known for its uranium deposits. Our multidisciplinary field party includes geochemists, geochronologists, geophysicists and geologists, eerts who have the collective goal of understanding how and why these deposits formed.
When we’re out in the field, we have to get up early. There’s always quite a bit of work to do in the morning, and we need to make sure to eat a big, healthy breakfast to get us through the day!

Today, we will be hiking through the bush to get some drill cores — samples of a natural material previously removed using a cylinder drill. While at the core storage area, we take samples and measurements from the drill core to get information about the subsurface. Sometimes the drill core is only accessible by overgrown roads, so it can be quite the journey tracking it down!
When we get to the location, it’s straight to work — everyone has their targets. Each one of us seeks to collect data to solve the research questions we formulated before leaving for the field.

Meet Jeremy! My colleague Jeremy Powell is interested in the low-temperature history of southern Athabasca. He’s combing the drill core for fractures and faults, using many different techniques to understand when these structures were active. Dating the movement of these structures and the timing of hydrothermal fluids that circulated through them will help us learn how and when these uranium deposits formed.

Kathryn Bethune is a Professor of Geology at the University of Regina. She and her Ph.D. student, Dillon Johnstone, are investigating the regional setting and related structural controls of uranium deposits in the area. The primary aim is to create a fuller -D and -D picture of the major structural features and their relationship to the uranium deposits, as well as getting a fuller understanding of the sequence and timing of structures.

Meet Eric Potter, a fellow research scientist at the GSC. Eric studies how and why these uranium deposits formed. For this project, Eric is looking for ancient chemical fingerprints of fluids that formed these deposits. This research is attempting to create a way of identifying faults that channeled the uranium-bearing fluids to the site of the deposit and addressing questions on how the deposits form.

This is Charlene, everyone’s favourite summer student! Charlene is starting an M.Sc. degree in geology this fall, so this eedition will give her some great hands-on eerience in remote settings while learning more about economic geology. Charlene will be taking detailed measurements on drill core samples, assisting with digital data management, helping manage the camp and contributing ideas to the deposit models.

Welcome to “Come dine with me Athabasca,” where Canada’s best and brightest government scientists battle it out to become ultimate camp chef! Because we are in a smaller camp, we cook our own food and each member is responsible for at least one communal dinner. This can often lead to some friendly competition as to who’s the best cook.

We may be done in the field for the day, but we need to go over the data collected, discuss our findings and plan our targets for tomorrow. Fieldwork often involves very long work days — but it’s worth it for the science.
Well, thanks for joining us today! We hope you enjoyed learning a bit about the fieldwork we do during the summer! Until next time.

“What will Canada’s energy picture look like in the year ?” Looking beyond their current work and eertise, participants of the Generation Energy roundtable at Dalhousie University were asked for their vision of Canada’s future energy mix. A diverse group — students, academics, Indigenous representatives, energy consultants, members of civil society — they had plenty of insights ready for Natural Resources Canada’s Minister, Jim Carr. Dal graduate Samantha Peverell provided her thoughts: “GenEnergy isn’t just about generating energy — it’s about saving energy, too.”
An insectiphobe’s worst nightmare! But studying dispersals in Eastern Canada doesn’t bug NRCan scientist Emily Owens.

What will it take to fight ? A team of the best clean energy “nerds” in Canada! One self-proclaimed “GHG nerd” is Anamika, who was profiled as part of the initiative. Anamika works with Cenovus Energy to find ways to produce oil efficiently while reducing the impact of climate change. “We live in a time where the world wants answers from energy sources and [wants to] transition towards a clean energy future. And as an industry, if we are to be sustainable, it is our responsibility to be part of that clean energy future,” Anamika said. Curious about what Canada’s clean energy “nerds” are up to? Visit for more information.

Student research assistants Nicolas Piette-Lauziere and Zoik Brault are in the field at the edge of Cape Breton Highlands National Park. They are proudly displaying their commemorative t-shirts! Over the last month, Nicolas and Zoik have been mapping a fault zone on Cape Breton Island that separates rocks with different geological histories on either side. By studying the fault zone in the field, and collecting samples to study in the lab, Nicolas hopes to discover when and why it formed, and how it may have created a pathway for magma deep in the Earth’s crust to rise and form granite.

– Canadian innovation was showcased during the forum. This battery-powered Eco-Marathon car was designed by , a group of engineering students at the University of Manitoba. The Eco-Marathon competition challenges students to design and build cars to see which vehicle can travel the farthest distance on a single litre of fuel. The car had to do laps on a one-kilometre circuit and was judged on its kilometres per kilowatt hours. The team placed th out of in the battery-electric prototype category in Detroit in April .

Here are two innovations that were showcased at the forum!The EV Garage is an interactive display designed to help Canadians elore and better understand electric vehicles and solar energy production for vehicles and buildings.The Chevy Volt is a hybrid plug-in electric vehicle. The car uses the battery power until the battery is empty, at which point gas can be used. The Volt has regenerative braking to help charge the battery.

Here’s another innovation that was featured at the forum.This is the EnCurrent hydrokinetic turbine.This turbine is ideal for power generation in remote communities. A kW version of this turbine is being installed in the Sagkeeng First Nation Community on the Winnipeg River; kW could charge a medium-sized home or business. This installation also gives NRCan a chance to monitor the performance of the turbine. These turbines have also been installed elsewhere in Canada, the U.S. and India.
